  const router = useRouter();
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  // Listen for binding errors from the popup via BroadcastChannel
  useEffect(() => {
    const channel = new BroadcastChannel("oauth-connections");
    channel.onmessage = (event: MessageEvent) => {
      const data = event.data as { type?: string; reason?: string };
      if (data.type === "github_error" && data.reason) {
        setError(ERROR_MESSAGES[data.reason] ?? `Connection failed: ${data.reason}`);
      }
    };
    return () => channel.close();
  }, []);

  const { handleConnect, isConnecting } = useOAuthPopup({
    provider: "github",
    queryKeysToInvalidate: [
      trpc.githubBinding.get.queryKey(),
      trpc.connections.generic.listInstallations.queryKey(),
    ],
    onSuccess: () => {
      // Re-render the server layout — it will now detect the binding
      // and render the full sidebar shell instead of this gate
      router.refresh();
    },
  });

  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    setError(null); // Clear previous error on retry
    handleConnect();
  }, [handleConnect]);

  return (
    <div className="flex h-full items-center justify-center bg-background">
      <div className="flex max-w-md flex-col items-center gap-6 text-center">
        <div className="flex flex-col gap-2">
          <h1 className="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">
            Connect your GitHub organization
          </h1>
          <p className="text-muted-foreground">
            Lightfast requires a GitHub organization to get started.
            Connect yours to begin.
          </p>
        </div>
        {error && (
          <p className="text-sm text-destructive">{error}</p>
        )}
        <button
          type="button"
          onClick={handleClick}
          disabled={isConnecting}
          className="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-primary px-6 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-primary-foreground hover:bg-primary/90 disabled:opacity-50"
        >
          {isConnecting ? "Connecting..." : "Connect GitHub"}
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

After the popup closes successfully, `router.refresh()` triggers a server-side re-render. The layout re-queries `getGitHubBinding`, finds the active binding, and renders the normal sidebar shell. If the binding was rejected, the connected page broadcasts `github_error` instead of `github_connected`, and the gate displays an inline error message. Clicking "Connect GitHub" again clears the error.

#### 5. Update org creation navigation

**File**: `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-allowed)/account/teams/new/_components/team-name-form.tsx`

In the `onSuccess` callback (around line 39), change the navigation target:

```typescript
// Before:
router.push(`/account/teams/invite?teamSlug=${data.slug}`);

// After:
router.push(`/${data.slug}`);
```

User lands on `/${slug}` → layout detects no binding → shows `<GitHubSetupGate>`.

#### 6. Delete invite page

Delete the entire directory and all contents:

```
apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-allowed)/account/teams/invite/
```

Files removed:
- `page.tsx`
- `_actions/invite-teammates.ts`
- `_components/invite-form.tsx`
- `_lib/search-params.ts`

### Success Criteria:

#### Automated Verification:

- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes
- [ ] `pnpm build:app` passes
- [ ] No imports reference deleted invite page files: `grep -r "teams/invite" apps/app/src/`
- [ ] No dead links to `/account/teams/invite` in any source file

#### Manual Verification:

- [ ] Create new org with slug "test-org" → lands on `/test-org` → sees GitHub setup gate (no sidebar)
- [ ] Click "Connect GitHub" → popup opens → install GitHub App → popup closes → gate disappears → full org home with sidebar visible
- [ ] Navigate to `/test-org/sources` directly without binding → sees setup gate
- [ ] After binding, all org pages (`/sources`, `/entities`, `/events`, `/settings`) accessible normally
- [ ] Existing org that has no GitHub binding → sees setup gate on any org page
- [ ] Existing org that already has a GitHub `gatewayInstallation` but no `github_org_bindings` row → sees setup gate (binding created on next connect)

**Implementation Note**: After completing this phase and all automated verification passes, pause here for manual confirmation of the full onboarding flow.

**Future optimization**: Clerk `publicMetadata` sync (storing GitHub org identity in the Clerk org JWT) can eliminate the per-request DB query in the layout. Deferred to a separate plan — it adds client-side timing complexity with no immediate benefit while the DB query is sub-millisecond on the indexed unique column.

---

## Testing Strategy

### Unit Tests:

- `enforceGitHubBinding` — test all 4 paths: create, reinstate, reject (github bound to other), reject (org bound to other)
- `resolveGitHubAccount` — test successful parse, missing account, API failure

### Manual Testing Steps:

1. **New org onboarding**: Create org → see gate → connect GitHub → org loads
2. **Cross-org rejection**: Create second org → try to bind same GitHub org → popup closes → gate shows inline error
3. **Revocation flow**: Uninstall GitHub App → health check fires → gate reappears
4. **Reinstatement flow**: Reinstall GitHub App to same org → binding reinstated → gate disappears
5. **Different GitHub org rejection**: Org already bound to GitHub org A → try installing GitHub org B → rejected
6. **Existing orgs**: Navigate to an org that has a `gatewayInstallation` but no binding row → gate shown → connecting creates the binding row

### Edge Cases:

- GitHub callback without state token (GitHub-initiated permission change) — existing fallback at `callback.ts:179-205` recovers `orgId` from `gatewayInstallations`, binding check runs normally
- Popup blocked by browser — `useOAuthPopup` shows alert, user retries
- Multiple tabs — `BroadcastChannel` signals across tabs, `router.refresh()` only runs on the tab that opened the popup
- Concurrent callbacks — `UNIQUE` indexes on the binding table prevent duplicate rows; `onConflictDoNothing` + `.returning()` check handles the race gracefully with a rejection redirect

## Performance Considerations

- **Layout binding check**: Single indexed lookup on `UNIQUE(clerk_org_id)` — sub-millisecond at the DB level, ~10-50ms over Neon HTTP. Deduplicated per-request via React `cache()`.
- **Callback API call**: One `GET /app/installations/{id}` to GitHub (~100-200ms). Acceptable for a one-time binding operation. Uses same JWT auth pattern as `healthCheck.check`.

## Migration Notes

- **Existing orgs without GitHub connections**: Will see the setup gate on next visit. They must connect GitHub to proceed — this is intentional per the "no GitHub = no Lightfast" design decision.
- **Existing orgs WITH GitHub `gatewayInstallation`**: Still see the gate because no `github_org_bindings` row exists. Connecting GitHub again will create the binding row. The `gatewayInstallations` upsert will update the existing row (same `installation_id`), and a new binding row will be created.
- **No data migration needed**: Binding rows are created lazily on next connection. No backfill script required.
- **Schema backward compatibility**: New `githubAccountInfoSchema` fields are optional, so existing `providerAccountInfo` JSONB values parse without errors.

## References

- Research: `thoughts/shared/research/2026-04-09-org-creation-github-binding-architecture.md`
- Org layout gatekeeper: `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(org)/[slug]/layout.tsx:40-52`
- Callback processing: `api/platform/src/lib/oauth/callback.ts:155-357`
- GitHub provider: `packages/app-providers/src/providers/github/index.ts`
- GitHub API schema: `packages/app-providers/src/providers/github/api.ts:59-71`
- GitHub account info schema: `packages/app-providers/src/providers/github/auth.ts:20-27`
- Connection lifecycle: `api/platform/src/inngest/functions/connection-lifecycle.ts:31-180`
- Schema template: `db/app/src/schema/tables/org-repo-indexes.ts`
- Team creation form: `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-allowed)/account/teams/new/_components/team-name-form.tsx`
- Root tRPC router: `api/app/src/root.ts:19-30`
- `createGitHubAppJWT`: `packages/app-providers/src/providers/github/index.ts:34-40`
- `healthCheck.check` (JWT API call pattern): `packages/app-providers/src/providers/github/index.ts:278-298`
- GitHub connected page (BroadcastChannel): `apps/app/src/app/(providers)/provider/github/connected/page.tsx`

---

## Improvement Log

Changes made during adversarial review on 2026-04-09:

### Critical fixes

1. **Replaced `getActiveToken` with `createGitHubAppJWT`** (Phase 2, step 1-2) — `getActiveToken` returns an installation-scoped access token via `POST /app/installations/{id}/access_tokens`, not a JWT. The `GET /app/installations/{id}` endpoint requires App-level JWT auth. Additionally, `getActiveToken` is a method on the `auth` object (not a standalone function), so "add `export`" was impossible. Fix: export `createGitHubAppJWT` (line 34, module-private function) and use it directly. Added `User-Agent`, `X-GitHub-Api-Version` headers and `AbortSignal.timeout(10_000)` to match the existing `healthCheck.check` pattern at `index.ts:278-298`.

2. **Removed dead error page, added BroadcastChannel error signaling** (Phase 2, step 4 + Phase 3, step 4) — `buildRedirectForError` redirects to `/provider/github/connected?error=...`, not `/provider/github/error`. The error page was unreachable. Fix: updated the existing connected page to broadcast `github_error` when `?error=` is present, and added error listener + inline error display to `GitHubSetupGate`.

3. **Added `onConflictDoNothing` + `.returning()` check to binding INSERT** (Phase 2, callback integration) — The two sequential SELECTs in `enforceGitHubBinding` aren't atomic. A concurrent callback could race past both checks. Without conflict handling, the INSERT would throw an unhandled 500. Fix: `onConflictDoNothing().returning()` — if no rows returned, treat as a race-condition rejection.

### Convention fixes

4. **Added `satisfies TRPCRouterRecord`** (Phase 3, step 1) — Existing org-scoped routers (`repo-index.ts`, `org-api-keys.ts`) all use this pattern for type safety.

5. **Removed phantom `lifecycleLogs` from `gatewayInstallationsRelations`** (Phase 1, step 3) — The current relation only has `tokens` and `orgIntegrations`. Adding `lifecycleLogs` was a drive-by change unrelated to binding.

### Scope changes

6. **Cut Phase 4 (Clerk publicMetadata sync)** — Added complexity (client-side mutation timing window) for no immediate benefit. The layout DB query on `UNIQUE(clerk_org_id)` is sub-millisecond. Deferred to a follow-up ticket when JWT-level gating is actually needed.

7. **Clarified `onDelete: "set null"` on `installationId` FK** (Phase 1) — Installations are never deleted (set to `status: "revoked"`), so the FK cascade never fires. The actual nulling happens explicitly in the connection lifecycle handler. FK kept for referential integrity and Drizzle relation inference.

